\begin_layout Section
Water budget
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interception model accepts precipitation 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 potential evaporation
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 and the current storage state of the interception reservoir 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{I0}$
\end_inset

.
 Its output is the state of the interception reservoir at the end of the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{I}$
\end_inset

,
 the amount that reaches the ground 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the actual evaporation from the interception reservoir 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 The water budget of the interception reservoir during each time step in the code reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{I}=P_{0}-E_{I}-\left(S_{I}-S_{I0}\right)/\Delta t-P_{1}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sum of the right-hand terms is zero,
 which is also verified during the simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then follows the root zone,
 which starts with its current status 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{R0}$
\end_inset

,
 and accepts 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the remainder of the potential evaporation 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}-E_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 What comes out is the state of the root zone reservoir at the end of the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{R}$
\end_inset

 the recharge 
\begin_inset Formula $rch$
\end_inset

 which is the overflow of the root zone reservoir averaged over the time step and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{r}$
\end_inset

 the actual evaporation from the root zone.
 The water budget for the root zone reads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{R}=P_{1}-\left(E_{0}-E_{1}\right)-\left(S_{R}-S_{R0}\right)/\Delta t-rch=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sum of the right-hand terms also equals zero in every time step and is verified during the simulation.
 The overall water budget equals 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{I}+B_{R}=0$
\end_inset

,
 so we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{I}+B_{R} & =P_{0}-E_{1}-\left(S_{I}-S_{I0}\right)/\Delta t-P_{1}+P_{1}-E_{R}+\left(S_{R}-S_{R0}\right)/\Delta t-rch\\
0 & =P_{0}-\left(E_{I}+E_{R}\right)-\left(\left(S_{I}-S_{I0}\right)+\left(S_{R}-S_{R0}\right)\right)/\Delta t-rch
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have precipitation 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 overall actual evaporation
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}=E_{I}+E_{R}$
\end_inset

,
 the total storage change 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{I}-S_{I0}+S_{R}-S_{R0})/\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and recharge 
\begin_inset Formula $rch$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model starts with a pd.DataFrame with fields 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RH
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

EV24
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which hold the precipitation and potential evaporation provided by the weather station converted to mm/d.
 The outcome is the same DataFrame but with more columns holding the results for each time step.
 Currently the time steps are generally 1D,
 but in fact,
 any time step size will work,
 because the length of the time step is obtained from the datetime index of the data frame.
 The added columns are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
IC In volume that was interecepte during the time step:
 
\begin_inset Formula $IC=\left(P_{0}-P_{I}\right)\Delta t$
\end_inset

 [mm]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
STO The storage level at the end of the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $STO=S_{I}+S_{R}$
\end_inset

 [mm]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
EA The actual evaporation during the time step:
 
\begin_inset Formula $EA=\left(E_{I}+E_{R}\right)\Delta t$
\end_inset

 [mm]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
RCH The recharge during the time step:
 
\begin_inset Formula $RCH=rch\times\Delta t$
\end_inset

 [mm]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
BI The interception water budget:
 
\begin_inset Formula $BI=\left(P_{0}-E_{I}-\left(S_{I}-S_{I0}\right)/\Delta t-P_{I}\right)\Delta t$
\end_inset

 [mm] (must be 0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
BR The root zone water budget:
 
\begin_inset Formula $BR=\left(P_{I}-E_{R}-\left(S_{R}-S_{R0}\right)/\Delta t-rch\right)\Delta t$
\end_inset

 [mm] (must be 0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore,
 all columns IC,
 STO,
 EA,
 RCH,
 BI and BR have dimension [mm] over the time step,
 while the storage is in mm valid for the end of the time step,
 and,
 therefore for the beginning of the next time step.
 This implies that the precipitation columns RH and the potential evaporation columns EV24 must also be in mm over the time step.
 This will be automatically true for daily values from weather stations and time steps of 1 d.
 However the model will also work with any other time step but then the user must assure that P and EV24 must be the accumulated values during the chosen time step.
 In fact,
 the model will even work should the time step length vary from time step to time step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
