\begin_layout Subsubsection
Throttling in the lambda model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Amount-of-throttling"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the 
\begin_inset Formula $y=E_{a}/E=\left(S/Smax_{R}\right)^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the degree of filling of the root zone for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 (not shown) we always have 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{a}=E$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

=1 throttling is linear,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{a}/E$
\end_inset

 increases linearly with the degree of filling.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\lambda<1$
\end_inset

 the throttling increases progressively with emptying of the root zone.
 In practice,
 judging from the curves a values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 between say 0.1 and 0.25 may well resemble the real-world relation.
 Which,
 of course,
 should be verified on the hand of real-world data.
 Linear throttling or throttling in accordance with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.5$
\end_inset

 intuitively seems too mild as evaporation will be hardly reduced as long as the degree of filling is above 0.5 to 0.7.
 This is why in the earth model,
 we split the root zone into two parts,
 an upper part with a filling between 
\begin_inset Formula $Scrit_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Smax_{R}$
\end_inset

 in which no throttling takes place and a lower part with filling between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Scrit_{R}$
\end_inset

 in which the throttling is linear.
 This way the lambda model and the earth model can be made to react more or less the same for most practical situations.
 The earth model in which the 
\begin_inset Formula $Scrit_{R}$
\end_inset

 plays a role is the model mostly using in practice.
\end_layout

